response: Performance of the Haka at international sports events. Waitangi Day as a national celebration of biculturalism. Teaching Māori language in New Zealand primary schools. Singing the national anthem in Māori and English.

reference: Sengupta, N. K. & Sibley, C. G. (2020). Intergroup contact and political attitudes among ethnic minorities in New Zealand.
response: Māori ownership of the seabed and foreshore. Reserving places for Māori students to study medicine. Rates exemptions on Māori land. Crown (government) ownership of the seabed and foreshore.

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Number of outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How many of your friends are [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = None of my friends to 7 = All of my friends)  Frequency of meeting outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How often do you meet your [participants’ outgroup] friends?  (1 = Never to 7 = Daily)

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Number of outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How many of your friends are [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = None of my friends to 7 = All of my friends)  Frequency of meeting outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How often do you meet your [participants’ outgroup] friends?  (1 = Never to 7 = Daily)

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Number of outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How many of your friends are [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = None of my friends to 7 = All of my friends)  Frequency of meeting outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How often do you meet your [participants’ outgroup] friends?  (1 = Never to 7 = Daily)

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Number of outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How many of your friends are [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = None of my friends to 7 = All of my friends)  Frequency of meeting outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How often do you meet your [participants’ outgroup] friends?  (1 = Never to 7 = Daily)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Number of outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How many of your friends are [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = None of my friends to 7 = All of my friends)  Frequency of meeting outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How often do you meet your [participants’ outgroup] friends?  (1 = Never to 7 = Daily)

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Number of outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How many of your friends are [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = None of my friends to 7 = All of my friends)  Frequency of meeting outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How often do you meet your [participants’ outgroup] friends?  (1 = Never to 7 = Daily)

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Number of outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How many of your friends are [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = None of my friends to 7 = All of my friends)  Frequency of meeting outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How often do you meet your [participants’ outgroup] friends?  (1 = Never to 7 = Daily)

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Number of outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How many of your friends are [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = None of my friends to 7 = All of my friends)  Frequency of meeting outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How often do you meet your [participants’ outgroup] friends?  (1 = Never to 7 = Daily)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

response: Support for empowering policies (adapted from Shnabel, Dovidio, & Levin, 2016): 1) [Disadvantaged group] should obtain much more power in the decision-centers of our society. 2) Institutions of my country should allocate more places to [disadvantaged group] as a form of affirmative action. 3) The State budget should be distributed equally so that the resources that are allocated to [disadvantaged group] are proportional to those that are allocated to [advantaged group].  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Low cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren, Postmes, Spears, & Bettache, 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Voting for political candidates who support the equal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  2) Signing an online/regular petition to support action against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 3) Sharing posts on Facebook to support [disadvantaged groups] equality. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)  High cost collective action (adapted from Van Zomeren et al., 2011): Would you like to engage in the following activities in the future? 1) Attending meetings or workshops regarding the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. 2) Writing letters to public officials or other people  of influence to protest against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group].  3) Attending demonstrations, protests or rallies against the unequal treatment of [disadvantaged group]. (1 = Not at all to 7 = Very much)

response: Quantity of contact (adapted from Voci & Hewstone, 2003): 1) How often do you interact with [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = Never, 2 = Less than once a year, 3 = Yearly, 4 = A few times a year, 5 = Monthly, 6 = Weekly, 7 = Daily) 2) How many [participants’ outgroup] people do you know, at least as acquaintances?  (0 = None, 10 = 10 or more)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Positive contact (adapted from Kelly & Breinlinger, 1995 and Tropp & Brown, 2004): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact is friendly? 2) You cooperate well with each other? 3) You interact as equals?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Absence of negative contact (negative contact, recoded; adapted from Barlow et al., 2012): When you interact with [participants’ outgroup], to what extent do you experience the following: 1) The contact was unpleasant? 2) The contact is negative?  (1 = Strongly disagree to 7 = Strongly agree)

reference: Hässler, T., Ullrich, J., Bernardino, M., Shnabel, N., Valdenegro, D., Van Laar, C., ... & Abrams, D. (2019). A large-scale test of the link between intergroup contact and support for social change. Nature Human Behaviour.
response: Number of outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How many of your friends are [participants’ outgroup]?  (1 = None of my friends to 7 = All of my friends)  Frequency of meeting outgroup friends (adapted from Tropp & Pettigrew, 2005): 1) How often do you meet your [participants’ outgroup] friends?  (1 = Never to 7 = Daily)

response: Structural awareness. Structural awareness was measured using seven items (α = .75) adapted by Tran and Curtin (2017) from the original scale by Gurin, Miller, and Gurin (1980). Participants rated their agreement with positions that reflect awareness of structural inequality, for example: “If ethnic minorities don’t go to college, it is because the schools don’t prepare them well.”

response: Outgroup attitudes. Outgroup attitudes were measured using items from Wright et al. (1997) General Evaluation Scale. Participants rated how they felt about Black/African Americans and White/ European Americans in general on a 7- point adjective scales: negative-positive, hostile-friendly, suspicious-trusting, contempt-respect. Items formed a reliable scale (αBlack = .94, αWhite = .96), with higher scores indicating more positive attitudes.

response: We assessed how often respondents had positive and negative experiences with Black/African Americans and White/ European Americans (Reimer et al., 2017; Stephan et al., 2002). Specifically, positive contact (αBlack = .94, αWhite = .95) was measured using five items: the degree to which participants felt supported, helped, complimented, befriended, and welcome in the intergroup interaction. ... The items were averaged, and higher scores indicate stronger perceptions of positive or negative contact.

reference: Twali, M. S., Tran, J., Stewart, A. L., & Vollhardt, J. R. (2020). An integrated model of intra-minority ally activism. Manuscript in preparation.
response: We assessed how often respondents had positive and negative experiences with Black/African Americans and White/ European Americans (Reimer et al., 2017; Stephan et al., 2002). ... Negative contact (αBlack = .84, αWhite = .92) was also measured using five items, assessing the extent to which participants had been verbally abused, threatened, ridiculed, made to feel unwanted, or felt intimidated in the intergroup interactions. The items were averaged, and higher scores indicate stronger perceptions of positive or negative contact.

response: Structural awareness. We modified the items from Study 1 by changing the general term “ethnic minorities” to specify the ingroup (e.g., “If African Americans don’t go to college, it is because the schools don’t prepare them well.”). We made this change to examine if structural awareness that focused exclusively on the ingroup inequalities would also impact intra-minority ally activism (see for example, Gurin, Miller, & Gurin, 1980). The reverse coded items had poor reliability with the non-reverse coded items (α = .56) so we removed the reverse-coded items which improved the scale reliability (α = .71).

response: I am now going to show you some statements that people have made.  For each one I’d like you to say how much you agree or disagree with the statement.  Again, there are no right or wrong answers, it is your opinion that we are interested in. 1. White people have more political power in Britain than they should. 2. White people have more economic power in Britain than they should. 3. White people get preferential access to better jobs in Britain than they should. 4. White people are more responsible for the level of crime than black people. 5. The police force provides greater support to white people than it should. (1 = strongly disagree, 5 = strongly agree)

reference: Bond, J., & Dixon, J. (2020). [Unpublished raw data on White and Black UK residents' support for collective action for the removal of public symbols associated with historical racism in England].

response: Now I would like you to think for a moment about the recent increase in activity with regard to the Black Lives matters movement.  In particular I would like you to think about the issue of removal of statues that represent historic figures who are now perceived to be overtly racist. I am going to show you some activities that people could do to support removal of these types of statues.  For each action, can you tell me to what extent you would support participation in these activities? 1. Signing a petition to the government demanding removal of statues; 2. Lobbying their MP; 3. Taking part in a legal and peaceful public rally in support of removal of statues; 4. Joining a neighbourhood project to remove a local statue or statues; 5. Distributing leaflets calling for support for removal of statues; 6. Voting for a political candidate who supported removal of statues (1 = strongly oppose, 5 = strongly support).

reference: Bond, J., & Dixon, J. (2020). [Unpublished raw data on White and Black UK residents' support for collective action for the removal of public symbols associated with historical racism in England].

response: This outcome was measured with an eleven-point response scale (based on Converse and Presser,1986): “Imagine a thermometer and indicate how warm or cold you feel toward people from the following groups. If you feel warm/more favorably toward a group, choose a higher number (50–100). If you feel cold/less favorably you choose a lower number(0–50).”(0 = cold,100 = warm; r12 = 0.48, r23 = 0.50). ... For intergroup attitudes and intergroup trust, negative scores thus reflected an ingroup bias, and an increase over time in either variable reflected change in the hypothesized direction.

response: Positive and negative contact before the intervention were measured with two items per outgroup, each with a five-point response scale (based on Barlow et al., 2012): “In the past year, how often have you had positive/good [negative/bad] experiences with people from the following groups?”(1 = never, 5 = very often; rAsian = −0.03, rBlack = −0.10, rWhite = −0.28).

response: This outcome was measured with a seven-point response scale (based on Reimer et al.2020): “People face different obstacles and enjoy different advantages in life. On average, how hard or easy do you think it is for people from the following groups to become successful in Britain today?”(1 = very hard,7 = very easy; r12 = 0.54, r23 = 0.50). ... For perceived (dis-)advantage, positive scores showed that participants saw themselves at a disadvantage relative to an outgroup while negative scores showed that participants saw themselves at an advantage relative to an outgroup.

response: This outcome was measured with an eleven-point response scale (based on Converse and Presser,1986): “Imagine a thermometer and indicate how warm or cold you feel toward people from the following groups. If you feel warm/more favorably toward a group, choose a higher number (50–100). If you feel cold/less favorably you choose a lower number(0–50).”(0 = cold,100 = warm; r12 = 0.48, r23 = 0.50). ... For intergroup attitudes and intergroup trust, negative scores thus reflected an ingroup bias, and an increase over time in either variable reflected change in the hypothesized direction.

For perceived (dis-)advantage, positive scores showed that participants saw themselves at a disadvantage relative to an outgroup while negative scores showed that participants saw themselves at an advantage relative to an outgroup.
